Lamu residents whose land was acquired for the Sh200 billion coal-fired power plant want the state to hurry up and compensate them.Some 975 acres have been acquired at Kwasasi for the project. Residents said the land was acquired three years ago, but they have not been paid.The National Land Commission has approved a list of more than 500 landownersto be compensated.Each acre will be compensated for Sh800,000. The landowners have been off their lands since they were earmarked for the site. They said they want the money to buy other land. The investing firm Amu Power has pledged to employ more than 1,000 Lamu youth, once construction starts. It will generate 1050MW.